	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Gray highlight sounds really weird but interesting. They'd probably look horrible without a filter.  I'll have to try that.  Or do you have example screenshots ?</div><br />I guess Blaster Master is a good example:<br /><br />*giant picture*<br /><br />Look how the same gray can be used for highlighting both green and brown, and it blends well with both. It really looks like light green at the top of the grass. Also, look at the black dithering at the bottom of the grass. Some black pixels actually blend with the green and create dark green pixels, resulting in a perfectly good shadow effect.<br /><br />Now look at the unfiltered screen:<br /><br />*giant picture*<br /><br />The gray and black don't blend nearly as well with the colors they are supposed to shade/highlight, and are very obvious.<br /><br />The benefit of using this trick is that you can practically fit 2 color scales in a single palette (a lot of games just use 1 gradient per palette), since black can shadow both colors and gray can highlight them. This increases the apparent amount of colors on screen, since there are more hues.</div>
<br />
<br />Is it just me or does anyone else think the emu shot stil looks better.

		

